&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About Kaiser Permanente&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="OutlineElement Ltr SCXW169500988 BCX8" style="-webkit-user-drag: none; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; user-select: text; clear: both; cursor: text; overflow: visible; position: relative; direction: ltr; font-family: &amp;quot;Segoe UI&amp;quot;, &amp;quot;Segoe UI Web&amp;quot;, Arial, Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;Kaiser Permanente is committed to helping shape the future of health care. We are recognized as one of America's leading health care providers and not-for-profit health plans. Founded in 1945, Kaiser Permanente has a mission to provide high-quality, affordable health care services and to improve the health of our members and the communities we serve. We currently serve nearly 12.6 million members in 8 states and the District of Columbia. Care for members and patients is focused on their total health and guided by their personal Permanente Medical Group physicians, specialists, and team of caregivers. Our expert and caring medical teams are empowered and supported by industry-leading technology advances and tools for health promotion, disease prevention, state-of-the-art care delivery, and world-class chronic disease management. Kaiser Permanente is dedicated to care innovations, clinical research, health education, and the support of community health. For more information, please visit: &lt;a class="Hyperlink SCXW169500988 BCX8" href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__http:/www.aboutkp.org/__;!!BZ50a36bapWJ!o6XvanKHXOYQqWsLYvMMHaVQie204BxvsDU2f5DJBFIHbba8O5wvw99Q6eKBoNGsvDUOqvp4rgQZlsMR$" rel="noreferrer noopener" style="-webkit-user-drag: none; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; user-select: text; text-decoration-line: none;" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(5, 99, 193)"&gt;about.kaiserpermanente.org&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;Join Prairie High School&rsquo;s Drama Club for a dazzling night of music, empowerment and unforgettable performances as students take the stage to perform &lt;em&gt;Six the Musical: Teen Edition. &lt;/em&gt;Based on Henry VIII&rsquo;s six wives, this high-energy show combines history with a singing competition to give the women a chance to tell their own stories in a euphoric celebration of 21st-century girl power!&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;a href="https://wa-battleground-lite.intouchreceipting.com/PHSDramaClubSixMusical" style="text-decoration-line: none;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:rgb(17, 85, 204)"&gt;Tickets can be purchased online in advance&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. The cost is $7 for students, $12 for senior citizens and $15 for adults. VIP tickets with seating in the first five rows also are available for $25. The show is rated PG-13 for brief discussions of trauma.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;All shows will be held in the Prairie High School auditorium (11311 NE 119th St., Vancouver). Showtimes:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;Friday, Nov. 14, at 7 p.m.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;Saturday, Nov. 15, at 1 p.m. and 7 p.m.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;Friday, Nov. 21, at 7 p.m.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:12px"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;Saturday, Nov. 22, at 1 p.m. and 7 p.m.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;NEWBERG, Ore. &ndash; When Portland Community College restarted English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL) classes at its Newberg Center in fall 2023, instructor Amber Bliss Calder&oacute;n was on a familiar mission: helping adults find their voice in a new language and community.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;Bliss Calder&oacute;n previously taught at PCC from 2004 to 2006 after a stretch overseas and graduate study. She has lived in Newberg for about 20 years and is now entering her third fall teaching ESOL at the center.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;It was really nice to come back to PCC, and especially in my hometown,&rdquo; she said.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;A graduate of George Fox University with a bachelor&rsquo;s degree in Writing and Literature, Bliss Calder&oacute;n spent two years teaching in South Korea before earning a master&rsquo;s degree from Portland State University. That time abroad, she said, reshaped how she teaches.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;I wasn&rsquo;t successful at learning the language when I lived overseas,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I know how isolating that can be and how you stay in pockets of comfort. It gives me a lot of compassion for my students.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;The &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.pcc.edu/locations/newberg/" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Newberg Center&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt; currently offers four ESOL levels on site, with Levels 1&ndash;3 delivered as integrated-skills classes that fold reading, writing, listening, speaking and grammar into everyday scenarios. Level 4 is available locally as a bridge, and students who want to continue through the full eight-level ESOL sequence can transfer to PCC&rsquo;s other campuses, such as Sylvania.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;We&rsquo;re teaching students how to negotiate life here, how to talk to a cashier at the supermarket, ask their children&rsquo;s teachers questions, or communicate with clients, bosses and co-workers,&rdquo; Bliss Calder&oacute;n said.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;Most students at the Newberg Center are native Spanish speakers, she said, but the classrooms also include speakers of Chinese, Tagalog and Portuguese. Their goals tend to be practical and urgent.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;When I ask, &lsquo;What&rsquo;s your goal?&rsquo; most say, &lsquo;I want a better job,&rsquo; or, &lsquo;I want to help my kids with their homework,&rsquo;&rdquo; Bliss Calder&oacute;n said. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re trying to provide a way they can do that.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;The center&rsquo;s location is critical, Bliss Calder&oacute;n added, because many ESOL learners work long hours and early shifts in industries that power the region&rsquo;s economy. She sees students who start between 4 and 5 a.m., rush home for a nap, make dinner for their families and then come to class.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;They don&rsquo;t have an hour to drive to Rock Creek or Sylvania or the Hillsboro Center,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;They need something right here in their community.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;Students at the Newberg Center often hold essential, but less visible, jobs. Many work in farming, landscaping, nurseries, furniture building and construction. A large share of women in her classes clean homes or schools, including custodial positions in the local district. Some are even engineers with advanced degrees in their countries.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;They are highly skilled people,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s just the language piece that&rsquo;s holding them back.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;The 13,000-square-foot Newberg Center opened its doors in 2011 and is one of the first projects stemming from passage of the college&rsquo;s $374 million bond measure in 2008. The college bought the 16 acres from the Werth Family LLC to have a central location in the Newberg area to serve a growing community with classes, transfer credits and training.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;The collaborative effort with the local community earned PCC the Partner in Education Award from the Newberg School District and the facility was awarded Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) platinum level for its energy efficiency.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;This year, PCC has shifted into a new era and has been working with the community to align offerings at the center. The college hosted a community open house at the center in October that attracted more than a hundred from the community that connected them to services and classes like ESOL or healthcare. This fall, ESOL enrollment at the Newberg Center is up by nearly 10% and total enrollment at the center for all classes is at 133, edging back up toward pre-pandemic levels.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;Since we relaunched ESOL classes at Newberg, we&rsquo;ve seen working adults choose PCC because they know these classes lead to real opportunity for their families and employer,&rdquo; said&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;Karen Sanders, assistant associate vice president of Academic &amp;amp; Career Pathways at PCC. &ldquo;The impact is community-wide. Amber&rsquo;s compassionate, experience-driven teaching has been&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;central to this progress; she meets students where they are and turns language learning into access, dignity, and momentum for Newberg.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;Bliss Calder&oacute;n believes the classes benefit more than individual learners. She points to parent-teacher conferences that run more smoothly when families can ask questions directly, and to workplaces that become safer and more efficient when instructions and concerns are understood the first time.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;You don&rsquo;t have to have a translator every single time you meet with parents or need to discuss a child&rsquo;s needs,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It helps the whole community.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;While other ESOL options exist in Newberg, Bliss Calder&oacute;n said students choose PCC because it offers a pathway, whether to clearer communication, higher wages or future college coursework. Several of her Level 4 students, she noted, have a degree in mind.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&ldquo;They&rsquo;re not here because it&rsquo;s fun, although we do make it fun,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;They have an end goal, which is to communicate better or to get paid better and that benefits everyone. They need a bridge to a new world. Our job is to build it, one class at a time.&rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;For more information about what's happening at the Newberg Center, visit &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.pcc.edu/locations/newberg/" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;www.pcc.edu/locations/newberg/&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:cambria,serif; font-size:12pt"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;u&gt;About Portland Community College&lt;/u&gt;&lt;em&gt;:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt; Founded in 1961, &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.pcc.edu/" style="color: rgb(17, 85, 204); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Portland Community College&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; is the largest post-secondary institution in &lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;Oregon and provides training, degree and certificate completion, and lifelong learning to more than 57,000 full- and part-time students in Multnomah, Washington, Yamhill, Clackamas, and Columbia counties&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;. PCC has four comprehensive campuses, 10 education centers or areas served, and approximately 200 community locations in the Portland metropolitan area. The PCC district encompasses a 1,500-square-mile area in northwest Oregon and offers two-year degrees, one-year certificate programs, short-term training, alternative education, pre-college courses and life-long learning.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

