&lt;h3 dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,sans-serif; font-size:13pt"&gt;Clark County Historical Museum Unveils New Exhibit: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Echoes of Fort Vancouver: How the Fur Trade Shaped Clark County&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Opening Reception:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; Saturday, December 13, 2025 | 5:00 PM &ndash; 7:00 PM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Location:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; Clark County Historical Museum, 1511 Main Street, Vancouver, WA 98660&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Admission:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; Free and open to the public&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;VANCOUVER, WA (November 2025)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; &ndash; The Clark County Historical Museum (CCHM) is proud to announce the opening of its newest exhibit, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Echoes of Fort Vancouver: How the Fur Trade Shaped Clark County&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;, debuting &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Saturday, December 13, 2025&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;. The opening reception will take place from 5:00 to 7:00 PM and is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;free and open to the public&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;Timed to coincide with the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;200th anniversary of the Hudson&rsquo;s Bay Company&rsquo;s (HBC) Fort Vancouver&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;, this exhibit explores how centuries of trade&mdash;beginning with Indigenous networks that predate European contact&mdash;transformed the region into a vital center of commerce and culture.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family:arial,sans-serif; font-size:13pt"&gt;Exhibit Highlights&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Echoes of Fort Vancouver&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; guides visitors through centuries of exchange and adaptation&mdash;beginning with &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;the extensive Indigenous trade networks&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; that crisscrossed the Pacific Northwest, through &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;the maritime fur trade of the 18th century&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;, and into &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;the establishment of Fort Vancouver in 1825&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;. The exhibit also examines the lasting impact of trade on the county&rsquo;s industries, agriculture, and cultural landscape.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;Key exhibit sections include:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Crossroads and Trade Routes:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; The Indigenous trade systems of the region before European contact.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
     &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Hudson&rsquo;s Bay Company:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; The rise of one of the world&rsquo;s most powerful trading enterprises and its North American expansion.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
     &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Life at Fort Vancouver:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; A look at the diverse people and communities who lived and worked at the fort.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
     &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Growth, Change, and Tension:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; How increasing American migration transformed the region.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
     &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Industry and Agriculture:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; The roots of Clark County&rsquo;s economic development.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
     &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
     &lt;li dir="ltr"&gt;
     &lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Asian American and Pacific Islander and Native Nations Today:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; The continuing contributions of Hawaiian and Native communities in shaping Clark County.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
     &amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
     &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;The exhibit features historic maps, artwork, and artifacts, including depictions of HBC&rsquo;s vast territories, reconstructed views of Fort Vancouver, and 17th-century fur trade imagery from the Metropolitan Museum of Art.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt;A special section, &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&ldquo;Impact of the Fur Trade,&rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="font-size:11pt"&gt; highlights how the overharvesting of beaver populations and environmental changes still resonate today&mdash;contrasting 19th-century exploitation with modern conservation efforts.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir="ltr"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

